Minister of Defence and Military Veterans Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula had her first walkabout to see defence equipment at the Africa Aerospace Defence exhibition. She was accompanied by numerous defence delegates and security officials as she viewed numerous items put up for exhibition. She went around the stalls of hanger 2 and introduced herself to all the exhibitors to make them feel welcome and appreciated for choosing to participate in the expo. Mapisa-Nqakula announced on Monday that South Africa was ready to host this internationally anticipated event. The minister spoke to engineers, manufacturers and inventors to try and understand the importance of all the defence equipment. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window.  She sought to also understand how manufacturing some of this equipment in South Africa could boost the economy by creating youth employment and skills development. This morning, President Cyril Ramaphosa officially and formally opened the exhibition in front of scores of international delegates and exhibitors. Ramaphosa encouraged all delegates to take advantage of the exhibition, ask questions, acquire and share information.